passages.text: **Snowflake 2Q26: Solid quarter as Platform Cloud vendors rebound**

Snowflake reported 2Q26 earnings after the market close yesterday that were much better than expected. Snowflake delivered a strong beat and raised guidance for the full year. The stock was up ~11% in the aftermarket. In our view, the key highlights of the quarter were: 1)Healthy CRPO growth (33%), 2) NRR growth incrementally improved (125%); 3) Increase in the guidance for FY26, 4) No indications of an increase in macro concern. In fact given the recent strength at the hyperscalers and MongoDB it would seem that the headwinds from Al seen especially last year have abated.

While we like the quarter and near-term outlook for the SNOW, the stock is priced to perfection and our long-term concerns continue leading us to remain on the sidelines. For sustained strong growth, we need to see SNOW winning in key areas such as Al and data Cloud capabilities against strong competitors. While Snowflake has launched multiple new product initiatives to expand out of the data warehousing market and expand its TAM, we think these newer initiatives are still in early stages and have numerous competitors including the largest Cloud vendors, and we need to see some sustained proof points before assuming meaningful future growth contribution from them.

**Snowflake (PT $221, Market-Perform) Snowflake delivered a strong quarter in both key** business KPIs and revenue metrics and the stock naturally reacted. Given the nature of this business, this stabilization should continue to benefit SNOW for next few qtrs, providing for stable near-term outlook. But the question is how much of the strength was macro vs all the initiatives. Near term we believe the stock is priced to perfection and maintain this multiple will be difficult and long term we worry about the core business and competition in Al and related areasAs such, we maintain our Market-Perform rating. We increase our PT from \(\)191\(to\)\\(221\)as we rolled forward our model and raised our target multiple from 11.5x to 12.5x to reflect improved growth outlook.
VALUATION COMPS TABLE
Source: Bloomberg, Bernstein analysis

Snowflake delivered an impressive quarter with \(32\%\) production revenue growth (5% above the street), \(125\%\) NRR (up \(1\%\) QoQ) and \(32.5\%\) RPO growth and beating on both gross and operating margins. The company also increased FY total revenue and product revenue growth by \(2\%\) . After 14 quarters of QoQ deceleration it was really nice to see the company deliver acceleration this quarter. Not surprisingly the stock is up in the after market ( \(- 1\%\) ).

While in part, we believe, this was driven by the overall improvement in platform spending that we are seeing at all 3 hyperscalers including the strong Azure acceleration at Microsoft (Link) and yesterday at MongoDB (Link), but you also have to give credit to the company on the quarter.

With management guiding to \(25\%\) to \(26\%\) Q3 revenue growth and increasing FY growth to \(27\%\) , both of which we believe they will incrementally beat (3- 4% given history), one question investors will ponder is whether the company can stabilize product revenue growth rates at this level or if they will continue to decelerate but at a slower rate.

NRR, which is a strong leading indicator of growth, slipped last quarter from to \(124\%\) from \(126\%\) in the prior quarter and rebounded partially to \(125\%\) this quarter and has been trending down. While the decrease is not an immediate concern, NRR needs to be monitored because it is a core metric in understanding future growth.

The other metric that investors needs to focus on is cRPO which grew \(33\%\) . With stabilization in NRR and strong performance in cRPO we believe that the growth trajectory should be stable in the near term. Given the stock price, which is priced to perfection, we are cautious on the upside potential. Given the long term concerns and increasing competition we would stay on the side- linings given this valuation.

While we like the quarter and near- term outlook for the SNOW, we continue to worry about longer term deceleration. We have previously written that CY24 was a tough year for software as IT had to focus on Gen AI but was, in most cases, not given additional funding or resources to build their competency in Gen AI. Therefore, IT delayed projects, optimized usage (which we saw at Snowflake and the hyperscalers) and put their top internal resources on building expertise in Gen AI. That caused many platform vendors and especially Cloud platform vendors, including Snowflake, Microsoft and MongoDB, to see revenue deceleration in CY24. Budgets improved in CY25 and we believe many organizations both received additional, and maybe even incremental budgets for Gen AI. This year we have seen a return to Cloud projects and Cloud migrations (which Microsoft management called out on their last earnings call). This helped Snowflake but the question is whether we are just seeing the spending that should have been captured last year captured this year or if this is sustainable.

Given the nature of the subscription business, we think the stabilization of key business metrics and the improvement in growth would continue to benefit Snowflakes revenue likely through full FY26. But we continue to be concerned longer- term. As discussed earlier this was a solid quarter with strength in the core but for sustained strong growth we need to see Snowflake winning in key areas including AI and data Cloud capabilities against strong competitors including the largest enterprise software companies and the hyperscale Cloud providers. Our concern for the longer- term outlook for Snowflake is based on four elements:

1. The core data warehousing market is not growing as fast and will be Cloud saturating and gaining market share to supplement growth is going to get incrementally difficult. 
2. Increased competition from incumbents (database providers, hyperscalers) and new entrants (like Databricks, and potentially from SaaS app vendors). 
3. The emerging question of whether data warehousing will be as important in a world where more / most important on-premise databases move to the Cloud and every SaaS vendor and hyperscaler offers their own data federation / data Cloud. 
4. Can Snowflake win in AI against very strong competitors including the hyperscalers that Snowflake runs on top of.

As a countermeasure, Snowflake has launched multiple new product initiatives to expand out of the data warehousing market and expand its TAM. We think these newer initiatives are still in early stages and have numerous competitors including the largest Cloud vendors, and we need to see some proof points before assuming meaningful future growth contribution from them.
Management is making their big bet on how their AI and the data integration / federation technology

We note that management called out how AI is impacting their deal flow and that the decisions process of nearly \(50\%\) of new customers were influenced by AI. Given the early stage of Gen AI and especially Agentic AI the impact of Snowflake's offerings is a positive sign.

Last quarter, Snowflake also announced the retirement of its current CFO, who is expected to remain in the role until his successor is appointed. Management stated that they are making progress on the new CFO but have yet to announce the new CFO.
We highlight the key points from the quarter below:

- Strong uptick in revenue from new customers: This quarter the revenue from new customers was substantially higher than we have seen in recent quarters and while there is a multi-quarter effect from a jump in revenue from new customers we will be watching to see if the company can sustain these levels.

- 2Q beat: Q2 Product revenue came in at \(\) 1.09B\(, representing\)32\% \(Y/Y growth and beating consensus by\)5\% \(. This growth re-acceleration QoQ (Exhibit 5) is mostly driven by migration of legacy on- prem data. Combined with the revenue retention at\)125\% \(, it means that this quarter's out-performance is driven by new customers (Exhibit 7). This squares management's comment that there were a few very large customers doing significant amount of migrations of new workloads that drove the out-performance.
- Note that while growth accelerated QoQ and YoY the compare was a bit of an easier compare this quarter.

- Raised guide: Management issued 3Q guide above consensus and meaningfully raised FY guide (Exhibit 4) on back of strong 2Q performance. Assuming NRR stays consistent for the next two quarters and considering the multi-quarter effect of new customer revenue, we think that company can achieve to slightly beat their guide which is their normal cadence.

- NRR improved slightly to \(125\%\) : After NRR slipped last quarter from to \(124\%\) from \(126\%\) in the prior quarter, it rebounded partially to \(125\%\) (Exhibit 6). While the decrease is not an immediate concern, NRR needs to be monitored because it is a core metric in understanding future growth. On the other hand, new customer momentum is contributing to healthy overall growth (Exhibit 7). A stable NRR is important as it will ensure that the growth will not decelerate quickly and combined with healthy cRPO growth and traction in new products, will give management as well as investors confidence of healthy growth this year (FY26).

- Strong cRPO growth: both RPO and cRPO grew \(33\%\) this quarter (Exhibit 8), and the cRPO trend has been improving. We note that for a consumption-based name like SNOW with quite some in-quarter revenue volatility, cRPO alone is not the cleanest indicator of growth; but combined with a stabilized NRR we think this should provide some comfort with meeting the 2H goal.
- 40% Growth on Azure: while AWS is still SNOW's biggest platform, its growth on Azure has been the fastest with 40% Y/Y growth this quarter for customers running on Azure.

- AI showing early signs of success but core workloads drove most of out-performance: management mentioned AI to be a core reason why customers choose Snowflake (50% of new logos in Q2 driven by AI related decisions), and that they are seeing budgets on AI projects from some large enterprises to be allocated to Snow. We think the revenue contribution from these early initiatives is still limited as this quarter's strong performance was driven by core migrations.

- Margins improved along with revenue: Non-GAAP operating margin came in at \(11.1\%\) for 2Q driven by revenue outperformance, 3ppts ahead of the company's guidance of \(8\%\) and consensus of \(8.2\%\) . GAAP operating margin also improved to \(-30\%\) as the company focuses on reducing SBC.

- Valuation: it has been quite a wild ride for the company for a while, and the valuation has gone through a roller coaster ride as well. Now with more upbeat guide, increasing management confidence, and potentially more AI optimism, we see a good set up at least in the near term. However, we think the valuation and expectations for SNOW have re-rated to perfection, which could limit the upside potential going forward.

While we like the stabilization in the business we continue to have a number of concerns worth noting:

- Competition: While SNOW's bigger differentiation lies within their analytics instead of storage features, we believe that going forward Snowflake is likely to experience intensified competition from Data analytics, data federation offerings (e.g. Databricks, Microsoft Fabric, Salesforce Data Cloud, SAP's Business Data Cloud etc.), as well as the Data Warehousing segment.

- We note that SAP, as an example, recently announced a far more comprehensive data federation tool that leverages both structured and unstructured data and incorporated Databricks into the offering. As more and more SaaS vendors add more powerful and expansive functionality it begs the question of where the data should be stored and where the analytics / AI should occur.

- Iceberg: While management has dismissed near-term negative impact from storage and is now discussing it could be a tailwind, we still believe that over a period of time, the pressure on Storage revenue remains as customers adopt Iceberg (so that they only pay compute costs and not storage costs as they store data elsewhere), which is 10-11% of their revenue. Even though minimal storage has moved out to date, the impact of a transition is going to likely take years and thus
could have an extended headwind to growth. We worry that the transition to Iceberg could what and where functions are performed.

- Al success: Al has become a big part of the Snowflake story, but the question remains how Al will impact the company and when it will become a meaningful growth contributor. Snowflake claims generative Al will be an accelerator to its business. However, a pivot from storing, managing, and analyzing data to leveraging Al is not going to be easy to deliver or to monetize especially when your data is going to be relatively easy to access by the hyperscale Cloud providers you sit on and where your data is stored. Our question is, since Snowflake runs on Azure, AWS, and GCP, why customers will use Snowflake's Al versus the Al capabilities of the hyperscale Cloud providers that Snowflake runs on top of.

- Snowflake's initiatives also position them in further competition with the hyperscalers, which is a big bet. Finally, we feel that it is possible the strategy pivot is an indication that Snowflake's core data platform market is slowing.

- Snowflake beat consensus on most metrics, including total revenue, product revenue, and margins (see Exhibit 2).- Total revenue of \(1.145B, 5\%\) ahead of consensus.- Product revenue of \(1.09B\) represents \(32\%\) growth, \(5\%\) ahead of consensus of \(1.04B\).- Non-GAAP Product GM of \(76.4\%\) ahead of consensus of \(75.2\%\) .- Non-GAAP operating margin of \(11.1\%\) , above consensus of \(8.2\%\) (Exhibit 9)- Net Revenue Retention (NRR) was \(125\%\) in 2Q26, 1pp up QoQ (see Exhibit 6).
Management updated FY26 guidance on revenue and margin guidance:

- Raised Product revenue growth for the full year to \(27\%\) from \(25\%\) previously. While this still represents a Y/Y deceleration (see Exhibit 3), the pace of the deceleration is more controlled.- Maintained Product gross margin of \(75\%\) - Raised Non-GAAP operating margin to \(9\%\) from \(8\%\) previously.- Maintained FCF margin of \(25\%\) - Note that in 1Q26, the company mentioned that aim to lower SBC to \(37\%\) of revenue from \(41\%\) and expects that percentage to continue to decrease year-on-year.
Management has also issued 3Q26 guidance that is above the consensus (Exhibit 4):
- Product revenue growth of \(25 - 26\%\) vs. consensus of \(24\%\) - Non-GAAP operating margin of \(9\%\) vs. consensus of \(8\%\) - Share count of 374M

We apply an EV/Sales multiple of 12.5x to our forward sales estimate 12 months out (\$17.2) per share and add cash of \$6.4 per share, arriving at price target of \$221.
Beyond the macroeconomic risks already mentioned, the Risk to our forecasts for SNOW include:

Upside risks: 1) SNOW could successfully expand into adjacent market and meaning outperform our expectation; 2) Successful M&A driven expansion; 3) Competitive pressure may not prove to be as intense as we expect.

Downside risks: 1) Increased competition from leading IaaS/PaaS vendors; 2) Change in customer's priority; 3) Data management and analytics could shift to the SaaS vendors, eating into SNOW's market opportunity
